<subSubSection pageNumber="768" type="multiple">
<paragraph pageNumber="768">
Lourteig (in 
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="768">Bradea</emphasis>
5: 339. 1990) wrongly treated this as illegitimate, on the grounds that its type (
<normalizedToken originalValue="Burman’s">Burman's</normalizedToken>
plate) was originally based on the Plumier plate that is the type of 
<taxonomicName authority="Jacq. (1760)" authorityName="Linnaeus" authorityYear="1753" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rosaceae" genus="Potentilla" kingdom="Plantae" order="Rosales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="acaulis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="768">P. acaulis</emphasis>
Jacq. (1760)
</taxonomicName>
. However, the protologue of 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Linnaeus’">Linnaeus'</normalizedToken>
name did not include 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Linnaeus" authorityYear="1753" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rosaceae" genus="Potentilla" kingdom="Plantae" order="Rosales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="acaulis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="768">P. acaulis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
so, as names cannot be made illegitimate through typification, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Linnaeus" authorityYear="1763" class="Liliopsida" family="Araceae" genus="Pothos" kingdom="Plantae" order="Alismatales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="crenatus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="768">P. crenatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is legitimate.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
